  "prompt": "How is the formula for average acceleration determined?",
  "response": "The formula for average acceleration is determined by analyzing how the velocity of an object changes over a given period of time. Acceleration is defined as the rate of change of velocity with respect to time.\n\nThe formula for average acceleration (\\( \\bar{a} \\)) is given by:\n\n\\[\n\\bar{a} = \\frac{\\Delta v}{\\Delta t}\n\\]\n\nwhere:\n- \\( \\Delta v \\) is the change in velocity (final velocity (\\( v_f \\)) minus initial velocity (\\( v_i \\))): \\( \\Delta v = v_f - v_i \\).\n- \\( \\Delta t \\) is the change in time (final time minus initial time): \\( \\Delta t = t_f - t_i \\).\n\nSo, the formula can also be written as:\n\n\\[\n\\bar{a} = \\frac{v_f - v_i}{t_f - t_i}\n\\]\n\nThis equation provides the average rate at which velocity changes over the specified time interval. Average acceleration could be positive (indicating an increase in velocity), negative (a decrease in velocity, often referred to as deceleration), or zero (constant velocity).",
